{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474489"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:21:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:21:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12202"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12202"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.64,0.2,0.02,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52121"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4730"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12202"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37439"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1046"},{"type":"tags","id":"3711"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7458"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7494"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8518"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52121"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with recurrent nosebleeds and heavy menstrual bleeding. She suffers from hay fever and uses an over-the-counter steroid nasal spray. Her mother and sister also have a history of heavy menstrual bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 120 g/L (115 \u2013 165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 293 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150 \u2013 400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAPTT 42 seconds (25 \u2013 40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPT 12 seconds (11 - 15)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations would be most useful in her diagnostic workup?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bleeding time","vWF antigen levels","Factor VIII levels","Fibrinogen","Factor V Leiden"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBleeding disorders can be categorised as disorders of primary and secondary haemostasis. Disorders of primary haemostasis generally involve platelet dysfunction, while disorders of secondary haemostasis involve dysfunction of the extrinsic and/or intrinsic pathway of the coagulation cascade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVon Willebrand disease (vWD) is the most common inherited bleeding disorder. Von Willebrand factor is a glycoprotein that assists with adhesion of platelets to exposed collagen fibres on damaged endothelium (i.e. primary haemostasis). It is also responsible for binding to and reducing the breakdown of factor VIII. As such, a deficiency or dysfunction of von Willebrand factor results in more rapid degradation of factor VIII and subsequently impaired secondary haemostasis as well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClinically, this may manifest as a tendency for bleeding due to poor platelet aggregation (e.g. epistaxis, menorrhagia, petechiae) as well as dysfunction of the coagulation cascade (e.g. haematoma or haemarthrosis).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe investigations show a normal platelet count, suggesting there is no platelet deficiency but not excluding platelet dysfunction. INR and PT are normal, meaning the extrinsic pathway is not affected. APTT is mildly elevated suggesting dysfunction of the intrinsic pathway. In this case, this is likely due to the increased breakdown of factor VIII.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations for vWD include \u003Cstrong\u003EvWF antigen levels\u003C/strong\u003E (low) and Ristocetin cofactor activity (low). The latter is used to assess platelet aggregation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBleeding time\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to investigate disorders of platelet dysfunction. However, its value is limited by the difficulties with standardisation, reproducibility and lack of sensitivity and specificity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELow \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor VIII levels\u003C/strong\u003E would support a diagnosis of vWD, however it is nonspecific and therefore not the most useful of the options presented. Factor VIII level would be of use if suspecting haemophilia, which is not the case here as the bleeding is predominantly mucocutaneous and the patient is female (haemophilia is X-linked).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrinogen\u003C/strong\u003E can be implicated in inherited (rare) and acquired disorders with both hemorrhagic and thrombotic manifestations. Examples include liver disease and disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactor V Leiden\u003C/strong\u003E is a hypercoagulable condition involving a mutation of Factor V.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Von Willebrand disease is the most common inherited bleeding disorder."],"references":["Girolami A, Luzzatto G, Varvarikis C, Pellati D, Sartori R, Girolami B. Main clinical manifestations of a bleeding diathesis: An often disregarded aspect of medical and surgical history taking. Haemophilia. 2005;11(3):193\u2013202."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37439"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12202"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37439","link